SIMPLE: fillet
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Fillet
<hw>Fil"let</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>filet</ets>,
<ets>felet</ets>, fr. OF. <ets>filet</ets> thread, fillet of meat, dim.
of <ets>fil</ets> a thread, fr. L. <ets>filum</ets>. See <er>Fille</er>
a row.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A little band, especially one intended to
encircle the hair of the head.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A belt her waist, a <qex>fillet</qex> binds her hair.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Cooking)</fld> <def>A piece of lean meat without
bone; sometimes, a long strip rolled together and tied.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ A <xex>fillet</xex> of beef is the under side of the
sirlom; also called <xex>tenderloin</xex>. A <xex>fillet</xex> of veal
or mutton is the fleshy part of the thigh. A <xex>fillet</xex> of fish
is a slice of flat fish without bone. ⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Fillet</xex> of a
fenny snake.⟦rdquo⟧</note> <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A thin strip or ribbon; esp.: <sd>(a)</sd> A strip
of metal from which coins are punched. <sd>(b)</sd> A strip of card
clothing. <sd>(c)</sd> A thin projecting band or strip.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Mach.)</fld> <def>A concave filling in of a
re⟦eum⟧ntrant angle where two surfaces meet, forming a rounded
corner.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Arch.)</fld> <def>A narrow flat member; especially,
a flat molding separating other moldings; a reglet; also, the space
between two flutings in a shaft. See <xex>Illust.</xex> of
<er>Base</er>, and <er>Column</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <fld>(Her.)</fld> <def>An ordinary equaling in breadth
one fourth of the chief, to the lowest portion of which it corresponds
in position.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <fld>(Mech.)</fld> <def>The thread of a screw.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <def>A border of broad or narrow lines of color or
gilt.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>9.</sn> <def>The raised molding about the muzzle of a
gun.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>10.</sn> <def>Any scantling smaller than a batten.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>11.</sn> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>A fascia; a band of fibers;
applied esp. to certain bands of white matter in the brain.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>12.</sn> <fld>(Man.)</fld> <def>The loins of a horse, beginning
at the place where the hinder part of the saddle rests.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Arris fillet</b></col>. <cd>See under
<er>Arris</er>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fillet</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Fillet
<hw>Fil"let</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Filleted</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Filleting</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To bind, furnish, or adorn with
a fillet.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Filleting</ent>⟦br⟧
